Walls:

Design Summary
There are 6 main sections to the system. 
1) Input files: these include traffic reports, queries, commands, cities & roads, record history, undo, and schedule delivery
2) Parse input: check what the command line arguments are asking for 
3) Graph Builder (Module 1): create a directed and weighted graph for cities and roads based on input files
4) Traffic and Priority Query (Module 2): create a hashmap for dynamic road costs, handle shortest and K path queries
5) Delivery Scheduler (Module 3): create a Queue for delivery tasks, a Sorted List for history/recorded actions, and a Stack to undo actions
6) Format Output: command line interface output, add arrows "->", paranthesis "()", and spacing " " for clear and clean output
Each module, although done seperately, had to accomplish secitions 1, 2, and 6. As mentioned, a various data structures were used for each module. Module 1, the Graph builder, used a Graph described above. Module 2 used a Minimun Heap, a BST with the root node containing the least value, in conjunction with Dijkstra's algorithm for finding the shortest path between cities and K paths, or the number of different paths between a source and destination. The Graph from module 1 was reused and a HashMap was created to dynamically update road costs. A HashMap effciently and quickly sorts and retrieves data compared to standard search. For Module 3, a Queue was used for delivery scheduling. The Queue nodes had both the route name and time of delivery. The History log was a sorted list by time, organized earliest to latest times. Finally the Undo Stack, first-in last-out as opposed to a Queue's first-in first-out principle, took the most recently added action, whether a delivery or record, and undid it by removing an item from Queue or moving History items back to the delivery Queue respectively. 

Lessons Learned:
Jo: Working in a team requires clear communication (in comments & in overall communication) and To-Do Lists are helpful!!
Sajeda: Making an outline before starting on the project, is the best way to approach any project.
Sajeda: unit testing is important before moving to the next module, and gradually adding module was an effective way that helps with debugging and maintenance.
Sajeda: Always tell your group about any modifications you make. Transparency is the key.
Alex: It is very  essential to work with a very cooperative team because it makes the work relatively easier and fun to do
Kaden: Be responsive, proactive, and ensure that any changes are properly disclosed to the group. Changes made or code snippets should be concise and understandable.
